<paragraph blockId="3.[116,766,506,562]" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis box="[154,267,506,530]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Etymology.</emphasis>
– The specific epithet refers to the highly atypical situation of having four leaves arising per node.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[116,767,602,1138]" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis box="[154,354,602,626]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Conservation status</emphasis>
. – 
<taxonomicName box="[385,604,602,626]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="quadriphylla">
<emphasis box="[385,604,602,626]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia quadriphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from a single locality northwest of the Masoala Peninsula at an altitude of about 
<quantity box="[308,400,666,690]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" unit="m" value="1200.0">1,200 m</quantity>
. The montane evergreen forest at this locality is included within the newly established Makira Protected Area, but the habitat of this new species is nevertheless under threat due to human pressure, in particular unsustainable slash and burn agriculture. Recent satellite imagery from Google earth [https://www.google.com/intl/ en/earth] suggests that the collection site and the surrounding area with in a radius of approximately 
<quantity box="[541,597,890,914]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" unit="km" value="1.0">1 km</quantity>
is forested, but from a distance of c. 
<quantity box="[338,393,922,946]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" unit="km" value="2.0">2 km</quantity>
the area is deforested or disturbed. Despite the intensive nature of the inventory conducted by MBG (
<bibRefCitation author="Birkinshaw, C. &amp; A. Lehavana &amp; R. Bernard &amp; D. Ravalonarivo &amp; P. Antilahimena" bookContentInfo="304 pp." box="[233,507,986,1010]" journalOrPublisher="Rapport. Missouri Botanical Garden, Antananarivo" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" refId="ref2301" refString="Birkinshaw, C., A. Lehavana, R. Bernard, D. Ravalonarivo &amp; P. Antilahimena (2009). Strategies pour la protection des plantes de Makira. Rapport. Missouri Botanical Garden, Antananarivo. 304 pp." title="Strategies pour la protection des plantes de Makira" type="book chapter" year="2009">Birkinshaw et al., 2009</bibRefCitation>
) in the region, the new species has been collected only once, suggesting it is rare in the wild. 
<taxonomicName box="[212,427,1050,1074]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="quadriphylla">
<emphasis box="[212,427,1050,1074]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia quadriphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is therefore preliminary assessed as “Endangered” [EN B2(ii, iii, iv)] following IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" box="[383,525,1114,1138]" journalOrPublisher="IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" refId="ref2546" refString="IUCN (2012). IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3. 1. 2 nd ed. IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge." title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3. 1. 2 nd ed" type="book" year="2012">IUCN, 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[116,768,1178,1938]" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis box="[154,239,1179,1202]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Notes. –</emphasis>
Several morphological traits collectively make 
<taxonomicName box="[116,273,1210,1234]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="quadriphylla">
<emphasis box="[116,273,1210,1234]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">E. quadriphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
unmistakable with the genus overall, including thickened wings on the branchlets, four weakly bullate leaves per node, the four subtending leafy bracteoles (in contrast with two bracteoles, which is much more typical for 
<taxonomicName box="[668,753,1307,1330]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[668,753,1307,1330]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and an evidently united (or mostly so) calyx tube that splits basipetally during anthesis. In addition, it appears that the fruits may be longitudinally ribbed at maturity (
<figureCitation box="[621,682,1402,1426]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[162,189,1829,1848]" captionTargetBox="[218,1414,310,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[168,1420,309,1763]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. – Eugenia quadriphylla N. Snow &amp; Callm. A. Abaxial view of leaf; B. Branch and subtending (ramiflorous) inflorescence; C. Detail of flower showing longitudinally ribbed hypanthium, splitting calyx lobes, and four subtending bracteoles. [Bernard et al.917, MO &amp; TAN] [Drawing: R.L. Andriamiarisoa]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5684420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5684420/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), which is atypical for species in 
<collectingCountry box="[375,505,1434,1458]" name="Madagascar" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[116,768,1178,1938]" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">
The splitting calyx lobes align the species morphologically in 
<collectingCountry box="[202,332,1498,1522]" name="Madagascar" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
most closely to 
<taxonomicName authority="N. Snow" authorityName="N. Snow" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ambanizanensis">
<emphasis box="[509,766,1498,1522]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia ambanizanensis</emphasis>
N. Snow
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Snow, N." box="[233,372,1530,1554]" journalOrPublisher="Syst. Bot." pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="343 - 348" part="33" refId="ref2789" refString="Snow, N. (2008). Studies of Malagasy Eugenia (Myrtaceae) - I: Two new species from the Masoala Peninsula and generic transfers from Monimiastrum. Syst. Bot. 33: 343 - 348." title="Studies of Malagasy Eugenia (Myrtaceae) - I: Two new species from the Masoala Peninsula and generic transfers from Monimiastrum" type="journal article" year="2008">Snow, 2008</bibRefCitation>
), which also has this trait, the two collections of which occur in the Masoala Peninsula at a distance of c. 
<quantity box="[234,304,1594,1618]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" unit="km" value="75.0">75 km</quantity>
to the southeast. However, the stamens of 
<taxonomicName box="[116,274,1626,1650]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="quadriphylla">
<emphasis box="[116,274,1626,1650]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">E. quadriphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are arranged in a distinct ring, typical of most species of 
<taxonomicName box="[225,310,1659,1682]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[225,310,1659,1682]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whereas the stamens of 
<taxonomicName box="[575,766,1658,1682]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ambanizanensis">
<emphasis box="[575,766,1658,1682]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">E. ambanizanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are spread nearly entirely across of the inside of calyx lobes (i.e., it lacks a well defined staminal ring). 
<taxonomicName box="[552,767,1722,1746]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="quadriphylla">
<emphasis box="[552,767,1722,1746]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia quadriphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[302,496,1754,1778]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ambanizanensis">
<emphasis box="[302,496,1754,1778]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">E. ambanizanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in lacking the numerous thick (probably succulent when fresh) bracts subtending the flower of the latter species, and its strongly and prominently thickened quadrangular branchlets and whorled (4 per node) leaf arrangement contrasts with the terete to slightly winged and opposite leaves of 
<taxonomicName box="[357,549,1914,1938]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ambanizanensis">
<emphasis box="[357,549,1914,1938]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">E. ambanizanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Snow, N." box="[564,697,1914,1938]" journalOrPublisher="Syst. Bot." pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="343 - 348" part="33" refId="ref2789" refString="Snow, N. (2008). Studies of Malagasy Eugenia (Myrtaceae) - I: Two new species from the Masoala Peninsula and generic transfers from Monimiastrum. Syst. Bot. 33: 343 - 348." title="Studies of Malagasy Eugenia (Myrtaceae) - I: Two new species from the Masoala Peninsula and generic transfers from Monimiastrum" type="journal article" year="2008">Snow, 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[804,1455,282,1170]" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">
The basipetally splitting calyx lobes found in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="quadriphylla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia quadriphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also suggestive of a relationship with Mascarene species initially assigned to the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Gueho &amp; Scott" authorityName="Gueho &amp; Scott" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Monimiastrum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1297,1455,347,370]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Monimiastrum</emphasis>
Guého &amp; Scott
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Scott, A. J." box="[996,1139,378,402]" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bull." pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="473 - 498" part="35" refId="ref2751" refString="Scott, A. J. (1980). Notes on Myrtaceae in the Mascarenes with some recombinations for taxa from Aldabra, Malaya, New Caledonia. Kew Bull. 35: 473 - 498." title="Notes on Myrtaceae in the Mascarenes with some recombinations for taxa from Aldabra, Malaya, New Caledonia" type="journal article" year="1980">Scott, 1980</bibRefCitation>
), which 
<bibRefCitation author="van der Merwe, M. M. &amp; A. E. van Wyk &amp; A. M. Botha" journalOrPublisher="Pl. Syst. Evol." pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="21 - 34" part="251" refId="ref3062" refString="van der Merwe, M. M., A. E. van Wyk &amp; A. M. Botha (2005). Molecular phylogenetic analysis of Eugenia L. (Myrtaceae) with emphasis on southern African taxa. Pl. Syst. Evol. 251: 21 - 34." title="Molecular phylogenetic analysis of Eugenia L. (Myrtaceae) with emphasis on southern African taxa" type="journal article" year="2005">van der Merwe et al. (2005)</bibRefCitation>
showed was nested within 
<taxonomicName box="[1212,1299,411,434]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1212,1299,411,434]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on ITS and ETS sequences, the species of which 
<bibRefCitation author="Snow, N." box="[1255,1400,442,466]" journalOrPublisher="Syst. Bot." pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="343 - 348" part="33" refId="ref2789" refString="Snow, N. (2008). Studies of Malagasy Eugenia (Myrtaceae) - I: Two new species from the Masoala Peninsula and generic transfers from Monimiastrum. Syst. Bot. 33: 343 - 348." title="Studies of Malagasy Eugenia (Myrtaceae) - I: Two new species from the Masoala Peninsula and generic transfers from Monimiastrum" type="journal article" year="2008">Snow (2008)</bibRefCitation>
later transferred into 
<taxonomicName box="[991,1080,475,498]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[991,1080,475,498]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Basipetally splitting calyx lobes also occur in several species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1153,1241,507,530]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1153,1241,507,530]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1280,1454,506,530]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Snow, N. &amp; J. W. Dawson &amp; M. W. Callmander &amp; K. Gandhi &amp; J. Munzinger" box="[814,1020,538,562]" journalOrPublisher="Candollea" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="67 - 81" part="71" refId="ref2930" refString="Snow, N., J. W. Dawson, M. W. Callmander, K. Gandhi &amp; J. Munzinger (2016). New species, new combinations, and lectotypifications in New Caledonian Eugenia L. (Myrtaceae). Candollea 71: 67 - 81. DOI: http: // dx. doi. org / 10.15553 / c 2016 v 711 a 9" title="New species, new combinations, and lectotypifications in New Caledonian Eugenia L. (Myrtaceae)" type="journal article" year="2016">Snow et al., 2016</bibRefCitation>
) and in South American species once assigned to 
<taxonomicName authority="L." box="[935,1090,570,594]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Hexaclamys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[935,1058,570,594]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Hexaclamys</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Landrum, L. R &amp; L. Kawasaki" box="[1106,1443,570,594]" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="58 - 536" part="49" refId="ref2576" refString="Landrum, L. R &amp; L. Kawasaki (1997). The genera of Myrtaceae in Brazil: an illustrated synoptic treatment and identification keys. Brittonia 49: 58 - 536." title="The genera of Myrtaceae in Brazil: an illustrated synoptic treatment and identification keys" type="journal article" year="1997">Landrum &amp; Kawasaki, 1997</bibRefCitation>
). Given the significant geographical distance between 
<collectingCountry name="Madagascar" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
/Mascarenes and South America or 
<collectingCountry box="[1262,1431,634,658]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
, a hypothesis of convergence of the basipetally splitting calyx lobes seems equally likely as homology (singular origin) of the trait. However, recent research (
<bibRefCitation author="Federman, S. &amp; A. Dornburg &amp; A. Downie &amp; A. F. Richard &amp; D. C. Daly &amp; M. J. Donoghue" box="[1152,1404,730,754]" journalOrPublisher="BMC Evol. Biol." pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="216" part="15" refId="ref2420" refString="Federman, S., A. Dornburg, A. Downie, A. F. Richard, D. C. Daly &amp; M. J. Donoghue (2015). The biogeographic origin of a radiation of trees in Madagascar: implications for the assembly of a tropical forest biome. BMC Evol. Biol. 15: 216. DOI: 10.1186 / s 12862 - 015 - 0483 - 1" title="The biogeographic origin of a radiation of trees in Madagascar: implications for the assembly of a tropical forest biome" type="journal article" year="2015">Federman et al., 2015</bibRefCitation>
) has corroborated previous suggestions (
<bibRefCitation author="Schatz, G. E" box="[1188,1342,762,786]" journalOrPublisher="ORSTOM, Paris" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="73 - 83" refId="ref2712" refString="Schatz, G. E. (1996). Indo-Australo-Malesian phytogeographic connections. In: Lourenco, W. R. (ed.), Biogeographie de Madagascar: 73 - 83. ORSTOM, Paris." title="Indo-Australo-Malesian phytogeographic connections" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Lourenco, W. R. (ed.), Biogeographie de Madagascar" year="1996">Schatz, 1996</bibRefCitation>
) of strong biogeographic affinities across the Indo-Pacific region, suggesting that the presence of splitting calyx lobes may reflect an underlying phylogenetic relationship among species bearing this trait between 
<collectingCountry box="[1006,1177,890,914]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1234,1365,890,914]" name="Madagascar" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, despite the geographical distance separating these regions. Tracing the evolutionary and phylogenetic history of species exhibiting this character will be a useful addition to preliminary studies that focused primarily on inflorescence structure among Neotropical members of 
<taxonomicName box="[1030,1116,1051,1074]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1030,1116,1051,1074]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Eugenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mazine, F. F. &amp; V. C. Souza &amp; M. Sobral &amp; F. Forest &amp; E. Lucas" box="[1132,1354,1050,1074]" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bull." pageId="3" pageNumber="192" pagination="94 - 97" part="69" refId="ref2611" refString="Mazine, F. F., V. C. Souza, M. Sobral, F. Forest &amp; E. Lucas (2014). A preliminary phylogenetic analysis of Eugenia (Myrtaceae: Myrteae) with a focus on neotropical species. Kew Bull. 69: 94 - 97." title="A preliminary phylogenetic analysis of Eugenia (Myrtaceae: Myrteae) with a focus on neotropical species" type="journal article" year="2014">Mazine et al., 2014</bibRefCitation>
). A silica gel preserved sample of 
<taxonomicName box="[1063,1223,1082,1106]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="quadriphylla">
<emphasis box="[1063,1223,1082,1106]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">E. quadriphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is available for DNA analysis, although it must be noted that the leaves of the 
<typeStatus box="[1409,1455,1114,1138]" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">type</typeStatus>
collection are heavily infested with fungal growth.
</paragraph>
